    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Robust regression, like M-estimation, is an excellent next step, as it's designed to be less sensitive to those massive outliers compared to standard OLS. You could also explore Generalized Linear Models (GLMs) and switch the error distribution from the standard normal to something more appropriate for skewed data, like the Gamma or Tweedie distribution. If you suspect the variance itself is changing with the mean (heteroscedasticity, which often goes hand-in-hand with heavy tails), using Weighted Least Squares (WLS) might also help stabilize your variance estimates. These methods aim to make your model fit the majority of the data without being completely derailed by a few disproportionate points.\n\nWait, this is almost exactly like the difference between a standard OLS model and a model that uses an appropriate likelihood for the distribution of the *untransformed* dependent variable, which can be a nuanced topic. If the outliers are truly the problem, robust regression is the most direct fix, it's like giving your regression line a thicker skin against the messy data points. Don't just throw away those extreme houses; in real estate, those are often the most interesting, albeit noisy, data points. Keep in mind that some of these advanced",
      "source": "target",
